##Basic Plotting The plot() function is the primary way to plot data in R - ex: we can plot a scatterplot showing highway miles per gallon as a function of engine displacement:

plot(displ, hwy)

  • an observation is they are the inverse of each other. The plot allows us the more easily pick out the patterns such as the more displacement of the engine the worse miles per gallon the car tends to get. ### Creating and customizing beautiful plots will be using ggplot()
  • allows more control and a nicer view of the plots
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy))

Breaking down ggplot()

from the mpg data, we again examine the relationship between highway miles per gallon as a function of engine displacement: ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) the ggplot() function creates a coordinate system that we can add layers to, and we have told it to use mpg to make subsequent layers. we can add scatterplot layer using geom_point() function, which takes the mapping argument. the mapping argument defines how variables are mapped to visual properties.

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, size=class))

why are we getting the warning Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.?

the reasons why are:

    1. size implies a quantity of some sort
    2. data could be hidden behind some of the larger data points

the next example shows using a grayscale

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, alpha=class))

notice the warning using alpha is not ideal for this type of discrete data

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy, shape=class))

there are only 6 different shapes, not a good idea for large amounts of different data

lets change the color of the points, must take out of aes section because it is not longer an aesthetic. the color blue is set as an argument of the greom_point() function, and not the aes() function.

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy), color="blue")
